(often in books borrowed from friends). "A book, I value," he wrote, "I reason & quarrel with as with myself when I am reasoning."Unlike the complete Marginalia in six volumes arranged alphabetically by author, this representative selection is chronological and footnote-free, with a contextualizing introduction and brief headnotes that outline Coleridge's circumstances year by year and provide essential historical information. Our own cultural taboo against writing in books is slackening in light of new interest in the history of the book. It will be weakened further by the extraordinary and now accessible example of Coleridge, who was a remarkably shrewd but at the same time a remarkably charitable reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBooks and reading. 0aMarginalia. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAeschylus.  aAnabaptists.  aAnaxagoras.  aAristophanes.  aAristotelean.  aBarrow, Samuel.  aCabbala.  aCalvinism.  aCharles I.  aCreation.  aDefoe, Daniel.  aDemocritus.  aEikon Basilike.  aEpicurism.  aEternal Punishment.  aFielding, Henry.  aGichtelians.  aHades.  aHammond, Henry.  aHeraclitus.  aHippocrene.  aInquisition.  aJacobinism.  aacoustics.  aanimal magnetism.  abastardy.  abody, of death.  abullion.  aclairvoyance.  adancing.  adesynonymization.  adichotomy.  aequality.  aetymology.  aflatting machine.  agenius.  agrammar.  aheterozetesis.  ahieroglyphs.  ahylozoism.  aidealism.  aimagination.  akathos.  alaughing gas.  aliturgy.  amadness.  amathematics.  amillennium.  aoneiromancy.  aoneiroscopy.  aopium.  apaneidolon.1 aJackson, H. J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400825622zCo-access DOI >> cl